<p><b>What is late transcendentals?</b> In “late” transcendentals, the treatment of exponential and logarithmic differentiation and integration is held until the concepts of the functions themselves can be explained in terms of the calculus now having been covered.</p>
<p><b>Did Archimedes know calculus?</b> No description of calculus before Newton and Leibniz could be complete without an account of the contributions of Archimedes, the Greek Sicilian who was born around 287 B.C. and died in 212 B.C. during the Roman siege of Syracuse. We will look at one of the many calculus problems he studied.</p>
